FAQs
Is it expensive to study in Cyprus?

Tuition fees in Cyprus vary depending on the university and program. On average, international students can expect to pay between €3,500 and €12,000 per year for undergraduate programs and between €5,000 and €15,000 per year for graduate programs. Additionally, living costs, including accommodation, food, and transportation, can range from €5,000 to €10,000 per year.
Do I need to speak Greek to study in Cyprus?

While Greek is one of the official languages of Cyprus, many universities offer programs taught in English for international students. Proficiency in Greek is not typically required for admission to these programs, though learning some basic Greek can enhance your experience and help you navigate daily life more easily.
Are there scholarship opportunities for international students in Cyprus?

Yes, there are various scholarship opportunities for international students in Cyprus. Both the government and individual universities offer scholarships based on academic merit, financial need, and other criteria. These scholarships can significantly reduce the cost of tuition and living expenses, making it more affordable to study in Cyprus.
Can I work while study in Cyprus?

Yes, international students in Cyprus are generally allowed to work part-time during the academic year and full-time during holidays. However, it's important to check the specific conditions of your student visa and the regulations of your university. Part-time work can help cover some living expenses, but it's advisable to ensure you have sufficient financial support before arriving.
